==English==
===Etymology===
Probably a [[blend]] of '''[[irrespective]]''' and '''[[regardless]]'''; first acknowledged in 1912 by the ''[[w:Wentworth American Dialect Dictionary|Wentworth American Dialect Dictionary]] as originating in western Indiana
[[Category:Portmanteaus]]

===Adjective===
{{wikipedia}}
'''irregardless'''

#(''mainly'' {{US}}) (''non-standard or humorous'') [[regardless]]

====Usage notes====
*Although well attested, '''irregardless''' is non-standard and can make the speaker or writer sound ignorant of the terms "irrespective" and "regardless". As such, it should be avoided in formal contexts and replaced with one of its synonyms.

====Synonyms====
*(''regardless''): [[irrespective]], [[regardless]]

===References===
*'''Irregardless''' is marked as an “erroneous or humorous form” in Webster’s New International Dictionary (1909).
*The Shorter OED labels '''irregardless''' as "chiefly North American (non-standard or jocular)".

